OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F163A1780758677
OL,1,Wj5hw1~{4k7juhw1{$             G2/3
OL,2,W+.-'"-$/*%*%*%/"-$/*%Q,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,3,GUK long range forecast
OL,4,
OL,5,COutlook for Thu 11 Jun to Sat 20 Jun
OL,6,FRather unsettled early in this period
OL,7,Fwith Atlantic low pressure systems
OL,8,Faffecting the UK. These will bring
OL,9,Fshowers or longer spells of rain at
OL,10,Ftimes. The wettest conditions will be
OL,11,Fin the northwest, with more in the way
OL,12,Fof drier interludes in the southeast.
OL,13,FStrong winds may affect parts of the
OL,14,FUK at times, especially the northwest.
OL,15,FLater in the period, higher pressure
OL,16,Fand more settled conditions may begin
OL,17,Fto become more prevalent, especially
OL,18,Fin the south. There will probably
OL,19,Fstill be some showers or longer spells
OL,20,Fof rain though. Temperatures are
OL,21,Flikely to be near or a little above
OL,22,Fnormal overall.
OL,23,QppppppppppppppppppppGSource: Met Office
OL,24,ANext Page  BWeather  CReg News  FReg TV
FL,164,160,301,260,100,100
PN,16303
SC,0003
CT,20,T
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F163A1780758677
OL,1,Wj5hw1~{4k7juhw1{$             G3/3
OL,2,W+.-'"-$/*%*%*%/"-$/*%Q,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,3,GUK long range forecast
OL,4,
OL,5,COutlook for Sun 21 Jun to Sun 5 Jul
OL,6,FMuch of the period may be relatively
OL,7,Fsettled for most of the UK. High
OL,8,Fpressure is likely to be in the
OL,9,Fvicinity of the UK bringing drier
OL,10,Fconditions, perhaps more especially to
OL,11,Fthe south and west. There are likely
OL,12,Fto still be some showers or longer
OL,13,Fspells of rain at times though,
OL,14,Fparticularly towards the north. Winds
OL,15,Fwill mostly be on the light side,
OL,16,Falthough spells of strong winds are
OL,17,Fpossible at times in the north.
OL,18,FTemperatures will probably be a little
OL,19,Fabove normal and it could be very warm
OL,20,For hot at times in the south.
OL,23,QppppppppppppppppppppGSource: Met Office
